  },
  {
    question: "Where is gold IRA metal stored?",
    answer: "IRS regulations require gold IRA metals to be stored in an <strong>approved depository</strong>—you cannot store them at home (this would be considered a distribution and trigger taxes). Popular depositories include Delaware Depository, Brink's, and IDS. You can choose segregated storage (your specific coins) or allocated storage (fungible metals)."
  },
  {
    question: "What fees are involved in a gold IRA?",
    answer: "Typical fees include: <strong>setup fee</strong> ($0-$300, often waived), <strong>annual custodian fee</strong> ($50-$150), <strong>annual storage fee</strong> ($100-$300), and transaction fees when buying/selling. Total annual costs typically run $175-$300/year. Always get a complete fee schedule before investing—reputable companies are transparent about costs."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I take physical possession of my gold IRA metals?",
    answer: "You can take physical possession only as a <strong>distribution</strong>, which triggers taxes (and 10% penalty if under 59½). An 'in-kind' distribution transfers the actual metals to you rather than selling for cash. Many investors take distributions after retirement when they're in a lower tax bracket."
  },
  {
    question: "What are the risks of gold IRAs?",
    answer: "Key risks include: <strong>price volatility</strong> (gold prices fluctuate daily), <strong>higher fees</strong> reducing returns compared to traditional IRAs, <strong>liquidity concerns</strong> (selling physical gold takes 2-5 days), <strong>no dividends</strong> or interest income, and potential <strong>dealer markups</strong>. Gold works best as portfolio diversification (5-15%), not a primary investment."
